# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agnes-hürland-büning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 19 November 1972 to elect the members of the seventh Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the first snap elections since the resumption of democratic elections in 1949, the Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest party in parliament, winning 230 of the 496 seats.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD's Willy Brandt remained chancellor after resuming his coalition government with the Free Democratic Party.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 27 April 1972 the opposition had tried to have CDU leader Rainer Barzel elected new chancellor in a constructive vote of no confidence, but Barzel surprisingly missed the majority of 249 by two votes.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] Rumours that at least one member of the CDU/CSU faction had been paid by the East German *Stasi* to abstain (in effect, voting against Barzel) were confirmed by Markus Wolf, former head of the *Hauptverwaltung Aufklärung*, in 1997.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] Nevertheless, the following budget debates revealed that the government's majority was lost and only the upcoming organisation of the 1972 Summer Olympics in Munich delayed the arrangement of new elections.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 22 September 1972 Chancellor Brandt asked for a vote of confidence, which required the same majority of 249 "yes" votes: it failed with 233 "yes" votes to 246 "no" votes.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] The members of the government did not participate (in effect, voting no) to ensure the vote would fail, however it would have regardless.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] This allowed Brandt to advise President Gustav Heinemann to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections the same day.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the tense campaign, the CDU/CSU attacked Brandt as being too lenient towards Eastern Europe and having the wrong ideas on the economy.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] SPD and FDP benefited from the enormous personal popularity of the chancellor, laureate of the 1971 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] He gained the support by numerous celebrities of the West German culture and media scene (e.g.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] Günter Grass), expressed by the slogan *Willy wählen!* ("Vote for Willy!").
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] Voter turnout was 91.1%, the highest ever since 1949.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] In 1970 the voting age had been lowered from 21 to 18.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD celebrated their best result ever, representing the largest faction in the German parliament for the first time since the 1930 Reichstag elections.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] It enabled the party to nominate Annemarie Renger for President of the Bundestag; she was the first Social Democrat and also the first woman to hold this office.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 14 December 1972 the Bundestag MPs of the social-liberal coalition re-elected Willy Brandt chancellor.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] His Cabinet Brandt II returned to government the next day, again with FDP chairman Walter Scheel as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] Defeated Rainer Barzel resigned as CDU chairman on 9 May 1973; he was succeeded by Helmut Kohl.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 7 May 1974, Brandt would resign in the course of the Guillaume Affair, after one of his personal aides had been unmasked as a *Stasi* agent.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1972-west-german-federal-election] The coalition continued under his party fellow Helmut Schmidt, while Brandt remained SPD chairman until 1987.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 25 January 1987 to elect the members of the 11th Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] This was the last federal election held in West Germany before German reunification.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] The SPD nominated Johannes Rau, their vice chairman and the Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, as their candidate for Chancellor.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] However, the SPD suffered from internal divisions and competition with the Greens.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] It was also unclear as to how they would form a government, as the Greens were divided over whether to take part in governments.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] One of the major issues in this election was the environment, after the Chernobyl disaster and other accidents.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] The coalition between the CDU/CSU and the FDP returned to government, with Helmut Kohl as Chancellor.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] The Greens came into parliament for the second time and seemed to be established on federal level.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] In order to determine the composition of the East German representatives in the Bundestag between German reunification and the first post-reunification elections in December 1990, the results of the 1990 East German general election were recounted, using the new states of Germany as constituencies.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] This was possible since the original election results were declared on the Kreis level, and the states were re-established by simply amalgamating Kreise together.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] The results in each Kreis forming a state were summed up to determine the statewide result.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] The recount fixed the number of Volkskammer members from each party who would be co-opted into the Bundestag elected in 1987.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1987-west-german-federal-election] The 22 Non-voting representatives of West Berlin already became full voting members on 8 June 1990, in advance of unification.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in recently united Germany on 2 December 1990 to elect the members of the 12th Bundestag, within the regular time of nearly four years after the January 1987 West German federal election.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] Due to the accession of the former East German states on 3 October, after which the Bundestag was expanded with East German Volkskammer delegates, the elections were the first democratic all-German elections since the early 1930s.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The result was a comprehensive victory for Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his governing coalition of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union and the Free Democratic Party (FDP), which was reelected to a third term (and a fourth in 1994).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The *second vote* (preferred national party, *first vote* is for a local candidate) result of the CDU/CSU, 20,358,096 votes, remains the highest ever total vote count in a democratic German election.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The elections marked the first since 1957 that a party other than CDU/CSU and the Social Democratic Party (SPD) won a constituency seat (Direktmandat), breaking up the dominance of the two *Volksparteien*.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The first (and only) time since 1957 that FDP won a constituency seat was by Uwe Lühr in Halle, home of Hans-Dietrich Genscher, the "architect of German reunification".
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] In addition, Gregor Gysi (PDS) won Berlin-Marzahn – Hellersdorf.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] This was the first election conducted after German reunification which took place on 3 October.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] Previously, the Volkskammer had selected 144 of its members which were then co-opted as Members of the German Bundestag and served until the end of the 11th Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] Almost 150 seats had been added to represent the re-established eastern states of Germany, without reducing the number of western members.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The euphoria following the reunification gave the ruling CDU/CSU–FDP coalition a dramatic advantage in both Western and Eastern Germany throughout the campaign.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] For this election only, the country was divided into two areas for the purposes of the five-percent threshold: the former West German states and West Berlin, and the former East German states and East Berlin.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] Second votes were counted separately in each area, and passing the threshold in either area was sufficient to enter the Bundestag and receive list seats.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] As a result, while the Western Greens (4.8% of western second votes) did not gain representation, their ideologically-similar Eastern Alliance 90 (6.2% of eastern second votes) did, with both merging to form Alliance 90/The Greens in 1993.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The Party of Democratic Socialism also entered the Bundestag with 11.1% of eastern second votes, despite receiving just 0.3% of the western second vote (and only 2.4% nationwide).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] However, the distribution of seats to state lists was not divided in this manner and still calculated on the national level, which resulted in the PDS receiving a list seat (Ulla Jelpke) in the most populous state of North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The German Social Union (DSU) under leader Hansjoachim Walther, a right-wing party modeled after the Bavarian CSU running only in former East Germany, failed to achieve the separate five percent hurdle, only receiving around 1% of the vote in the eastern states, mostly in the southeast.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] As part of the co-option, the DSU had previously had eight Members of the Bundestag, who sat as guests in the CDU/CSU caucus.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The CSU, which had heavily supported the DSU financially, severed its ties in 1993 and the party fell into irrelevancy.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] All change figures are relative to the Bundestag as it existed after the grant of full voting member status to West Berlin's delegation and co-optation of Volkskammer members to represent East Germany.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The governing CDU/CSU-FDP coalition was returned to office with a landslide majority, and Helmut Kohl remained chancellor.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/1990-german-federal-election] The CDU did exceptionally well in the former East Germany, which had been the heartland of the SPD before the Nazi era.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Adolf Spies von Büllesheim was born in Haus Hall in Ratheim, district of Heinsberg, in North Rhine-Westphalia, property of the baronial Spies von Büllesheim family since the 18th century.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] He was the son of Egon Franz Freiherr Spies von Büllesheim and his wife Maria (born Freiin von Oer).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After school in Erkelenz he studied German law and farming at universities in Cologne and in Bonn.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] After university he worked as a farmer and a lawyer from 1960 to 1997.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Since 1952 Spies von Büllesheim was a member of the CDU political party.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1969 to 1972 he was mayor of Hückelhoven.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] From 1972 to 1987 Spies von Büllesheim was member of the German Bundestag for Heinsberg.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] Spies von Büllesheim was married to Gräfin Maria Immaculata (born Concha) von Mirbach-Harff, Freiin von Vittinghoff (1938–2002), and together they had six children.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-freiherr-spies-von-büllesheim] CDU Hückelhoven.de: Die CDU Hückelhoven trauert um ihren Ehrenvorsitzenden Dr.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller joined the CDU in 1945 and was later elected to the state executive of the CDU Rhineland.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] Müller was a member of the German Bundestag from 1961 to 1987.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] He had always entered parliament via the North Rhine-Westphalia state list.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] The social policy expert was Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour from 1965 to 1969 and Deputy Chairman of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs from 1969 to September 1981.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-müller-politician-born-1916] From 1981 to 1987 he was deputy chairman of the CDU/CSU parliamentary group in the Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] Born in Holzhausen, Homberg, Schmidt became a mechanic at a coal mine, then in 1942 was drafted into the navy as a submarine mechanic.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] He was taken as a prisoner of war and released at the end of the war, returning to the pit.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] In 1947, he joined the Union of Mining and Energy (IG BE), and immediately won election to the works council at the mine.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] In 1949, he joined the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), and the following year he studied in Frankfurt.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] In 1951, Schmidt began working full-time for IG BE, as its Munich youth secretary, then he successively ran the union's offices in Breisgau and Gießen, before in 1965 he became head of the union's Hesse-Rhineland-Palatinate district, and also won election to its executive.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] In 1969, Schmidt was elected as the president of IG BE, on a platform of improving working conditions in coal mines, and preserving jobs in coal mining and at nuclear power stations.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] In 1971, he was additionally elected as president of the Miners' International Federation, and in 1972 he was elected as an SPD member of the Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/adolf-schmidt] Schmidt stood down from his international post in 1984, as president of the IG BE in 1985, and from the Bundestag in 1987.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] It later emerged that she had become entangled, as an industry lobbyist, in the CDU donations scandal.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The prosecutors' office in Düsseldorf launched an investigation against her in respect of allegations involving serious fraud, false statements and tax evasion, but by 2007 she was seriously ill and the case was suspended.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] It was dropped in 2008 on account of Hürland-Büning's "permanent incapacity to deal with matters" (*"wegen dauernder Verhandlungsunfähigkeit der Angeklagten"*).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Agnes Oleynik was born into a Roman Catholic family in Holsterhausen, a small town on the western fringes of Dorsten (into which it was formally subsumed in 1943), a mid-sized mining and industrial town north of Essen, a short distance to the east of the Dutch frontier and Nijmegen.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She was enrolled at the local Catholic school in 1932.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] War broke out when she was 13 and troops were stationed at the school: teaching immediately became more "irregular" (*"... sehr unregelmäßig"*), especially after the children were sent to take part in combined classes at one of the two nearby protestant schools.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She completed her schooling young, with others in her cohort, in the spring of 1940, and was conscripted into the Labour Service (*"Reichsarbeitsdienst"*).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She was later sent to work in a munitions factory.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] After war ended, in May 1945, she worked as a volunteer nurse before moving on to complete an apprenticeship as a carer at the "Westfalia Welfare College" (*"Westfälische Wohlfahrtsschule"*) in Münster.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Sources are for the most part silent about her marriage, but by 1960, when she returned to the labour market, it was as Agnes Hürland, the mother of four or five children.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She was employed, till 1968, as a secretary / senior support worker (*"Chefassistentin"*) with an industrial business.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She worked for two years for the national labour agency.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] After that there were two years as a rehabilitation counsellor.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] There are also references to her having worked as an insurance and real-estate broker (*"Immobilienmaklerin"*) during the 1960s and / or early 1970s.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] By 1969 her marriage had ended in divorce: there is a mention of her husband having been affected by alcoholism.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] After a brief flirtation with the centre-left Social Democratic Party (SPD) – "because I confused 'social' with 'social democratic'" – Agnes Hürland-Büning joined the centre-right CDU in 1964.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She served as a local councillor in Dorsten between 1969 and 1975, taking a particular interest in social policy.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Her career as a national politician started only when she was.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Her inclusion on the CDU candidate list for North Rhine-Westphalia resulted, according to one unsympathetic source, from the party's introduction of gender quotas.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] As a result, she found herself elected to the Bundestag in 1972.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Nationally the election result was a close one, and many commentators were surprised when, following coalition negotiations, the SPD's Willy Brandt returned to power as Chancellor, while the CDU remained in opposition.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning became a member of the Bundestag Committee for Labour and Social Affairs, in which she took a particular interest in to the needs of the disabled.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Helmut Kohl took over as CDU party leader in 1973.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Apart from her committee work she maintained a low profile in the Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Kohl nevertheless valued her as a loyal party stalwart and when, in 1982, power finally passed to the CDU, Chancellor Kohl appointed her as "party business leader" (*" Fraktions-Geschäftsführerin"*) in the chamber.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She became known for her humanity, warmth, and willingness to reach out and make informal alliances with members of rival parties.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Even so, evidence of her political impact was limited.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Described by colleagues and observers – sometimes admiringly and sometimes disparagingly – as "the mother of the CDU/CSU party Bundestag group", one underwhelmed commentator suggested that she was at her happiest when organising the annual early summer asparagus lunch for the CDU Bundestag faction.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Directly after the 1987 election Chancellor Kohl made Hürland-Büning his secretary of state for defence.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She had no great specialist knowledge of defence matters, but many felt that her human qualities more than compensated for a lack of technical expertise.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Her grandmotherly manner, on display when she visited young recruits and junior officers, provided a reassuring picture.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Indeed, her appointment found support not just within the governing coalition parties but also from the SPD which was the principal opposition party.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She was the first woman to hold the post.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She paid particular attention to the welfare of the junior ranks.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] One development that she oversaw was a pilot project for the recruitment of female soldiers (on a volunteer basis).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She continued to enjoy a close political relationship with Helmut Kohl.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] In a prescient remark during a visit to the Knesset in Jerusalem she noted that if anyone could achieve German reunification, it was Helmut Kohl.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Commentators also note that her position within the Ministry of Defence meant that military contracts worth million of marks crossed Agnes Hürland-Büning's desk.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] 1990 was the year of German reunification, and the first general election of the newly unified country took place on 2 December 1990.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] By now approximately six months short of her sixty-fifth birthday, Hürland-Büning did not stand for re-election.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She accordingly retired from the Bundestag early in 1991, ahead of the new parliamentary session.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] She retired with her reputation in robust good order, awarded (among other honours) the Order of Merit (*"Große Bundesverdienstkreuz der Bundesrepublik"*) and the Order of Olga.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] However, the name of Agnes Hürland-Büning hit the headlines towards the end of that year in connection with the emerging CDU donations scandal: more details of her alleged involvement in those events, most of which dated back to 1992, appeared in Der Spiegel in January 2000.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Hürland-Büning resigned her membership of the Weizsäcker Commission on 20 January 2000, a few days after the Spiegel piece appeared.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Her involvement in transferring members of the old East German People's Army to the Bundeswehr was also abruptly terminated when she was dismissed by means of a telephone call from Defences Minister Scharping.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] According to the report of a parliamentary committee of enquiry, after retiring from her position with the Ministry of Defence, Agnes Hürland-Büning concluded several high-value "dubious consultancy agreements".
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Just two of the agreements, those with Thyssen AG and Elf Aquitaine, yielded fees amounting to eight and a half or nine and a half million Marks.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] (Sources differ.) What she had to do for all this money never became entirely clear.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] However, investigators felt that this may have amounted, at best, to an incomplete explanation, especially given that eight years later the pipeline construction in question had never taken place, apparently for unrelated reasons.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators appear never fully to have plumbed the suspected depths of the so-called Leuna affair, which sources imply may have been focused not so much on the personal enrichment of top politicians as on the garnering of funds to cover the political expenses incurred by the CDU.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigators felt that the massive fees received by Hürland-Büning were completely disproportionate to anything that she might have done to earn them.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] There was also widespread speculation that even if she had received the fees stated, it had never been intended that she should be the ultimate recipient.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The suspicion persisted that she had passed on the funds in the wider context of the Leuna affair and of the associated CDU donations scandal.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] One member of the parliamentary committee was Friedhelm Julius Beucher of the SPD.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] He described Hürland-Büning as a "living money-laundering system for the [Christian Democratic] Union (CDU).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] I think the lady's involvement was as the suitcase carrier" (*eine "lebende Geldwaschanlage der Union.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Ich glaube, die Dame war als Kofferträgerin aktiv."*).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] In the words of one commentator, the suspected contents of the suitcase were "black money for Kohl's black coffers" (*"schwarzes Geld für Kohls schwarze Kassen"*).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Nevertheless, it was clear from much of the media comment that many suspected that Hürland-Büning had also enriched herself along the way.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Investigations by the prosecutors' office were followed by the issuance of charges in December 2003.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Once her consultancy activities had been defined as a business it became liable for substantial arrears of unpaid business tax to the municipality.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] During her final years, with the threat of legal sanctions hanging over her, and a new generation of leaders controlling the CDU, there are indications that Hürland-Büning felt abandoned by those who had previously been friends.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Her former mentor Helmut Kohl increasingly withdrew from public life after the CDU donations scandal became public, especially following the tragic death of his first wife in 2001.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Within the little town of Dorsten there emerges a sense, from some sources, that family members and remaining friends felt that the work she had been able to do for individual citizens with problems, for Dorsten businesses, and for the town more generally, were all too quickly forgotten.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Meanwhile, at her criminal trial matters took a new twist in September 2004 when her defence lawyer submitted a doctor's certificate attesting that the 78 year old defendant's deteriorating health meant that she was no longer sufficiently fit to enable a fair trial take place.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Although it would take more than three more years for the court to reach a final decision in respect of the medical evidence, it was becoming increasingly likely that Agnes Hürland-Büning would go to the grave unconvicted but without her name ever being cleared.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] That was indeed the position on 9 March 2009 when she died following a major operation.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Only her family and a small number of close friends were present at her burial.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Her parliamentary colleagues were represented by a wreath that arrived from the Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Since then she has been commemorated each year by a further wreath, sent on All Saints' Day, and decorated with the black/red/gold sash of the CDU/CSU, on behalf of her Bundestag former party colleagues and their successors in Berlin.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2011 insolvency proceedings were launched against the estate of Agnes Hürland-Büning in respect of around €200,000 in unpaid business taxes payable to the municipality of Dorsten at the time of her death.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] By 2011 the debt had been reduced to around €170,000 by means of monthly payments of €1,000.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The city maintained its claim for the balance through the bankruptcy.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The business tax claim by the municipality had already been the subject of major disagreements within the council as far back as 2002.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] At that point CDU councillors, with their controlling majority, had agreed to a compromise deal with their high-profile debtor, freezing the debt and hoping, by means of the agreement, at least to secure monthly repayments of €1,000.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] SPD and Green Party councillors had opposed the settlement while the FDP councillors had abstained in the vote.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The CDU share of the votes in the local council election slipped below 50% in 2009, although they remained the largest single party, with 22 of the 44 council seats.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2012, during an interview concerning the state of municipal finances, a reporter asked the Dorsten town treasurer – another CDU councillor – about the prospects of recovering the unpaid business taxes of former CDU Bundestag member Agnes Hürland-Büning.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The treasurer declined to speculate on how much money would become available at the conclusion of the insolvency proceedings.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Bundesautobahn 31 runs parallel with the Dutch frontier, linking Emden in the north with Bottrop to the south.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The section passing to the west of Dorsten was completed and opened in 1989.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Between Junctions 37 and 38 there is an unmarked junction, without signage and without a junction number.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The unmarked junction was not included in the plans for the road, and only those with local knowledge are aware that it can be accessed by leaving or joining the Autobahn where maps and signs indicate a parking area ("Parkplatz Dorsten-Holsterhausen").
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The limited access junction only permits traffic to join the Autobahn in a southerly direction, towards Bottrop (and, indirectly, Bonn) or to leave the Autobahn travelling north (from Bottrop and, indirectly, Bonn).
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The rumour gained added traction after the name of the former secretary of state began to appear in press reports connecting her with the CDU donations scandal.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Der Spiegel gave it national coverage in 2000 and repeated it in 2002.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] In 2009 the pupils in class 9a at the Gymnasium St.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Ursula (secondary school) undertook what turned out to be an award winning investigation into the origins of the *"Hürlandausfahrt"*.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Arnold Erwig, their politics teacher, admitted that at the outset he had always assumed the rumours were true.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Only a few were prepared to have their voices recorded.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The town council had indeed objected to the Autobahn plans which had specified a junction at the hamlet of Schembeck, to the north, and a junction at Dorsten-West, some distance to the south.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] The city father demanded an extra Autobahn junction, but without success.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] They then invoked their local representative in the Bundestag.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Through her relationship with Chancellor Kohl, it turned out that Agnes Hürland-Büning did enjoy more influence with the transport planners than might have been expected.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Even her lobbying powers were not sufficient to provide for a complete additional junction, but the unmarked junction, accessible through the parking area, represented a compromise for which the city council at the time was appreciative.
[src:agnes-hürland-büning/agnes-hürland-büning] Those with the necessary local knowledge were able to save themselves time by using the "secret" junction: at the time that did indeed includes Agnes Hürland-Büning herself.
